The New Moral Landscape: What It Means to Be “Good” in the Age of AI

In 2024, Norwegian firm Strise ran experiments showing ChatGPT could be manipulated into providing detailed advice on money laundering across borders and methods to help businesses evade Western sanctions against Russia, including bans on cross-border payments and arms sales. Co-founder Marit Rødevand described it as having a corrupt financial adviser on your desktop. The bypass worked by asking questions indirectly or having the chatbot take on a persona.

A recent NBC News weapons investigation tested four of OpenAI's models and found that two of them could be jailbroken into generating hundreds of responses with instructions on how to create homemade explosives, maximize human suffering with chemical agents, create napalm, disguise a biological weapon, and build a nuclear bomb. Those two models were tricked into providing harmful responses 243 out of 250 times — a 97.2% success rate. Sarah Meyers West, co-executive director of AI Now, told NBC News, "That OpenAI's guardrails are so easily tricked illustrates why it's particularly important to have robust pre-deployment testing of AI models before they cause substantial harm to the public. Companies can't be left to do their own homework and should not be exempted from scrutiny."

It is an incredible thing to be a person who develops a tool that will usher in an entirely new age of information and redefine how we live in the world — a tool that might supply information to destroy a country or save millions of lives. You hope that it will do the latter. You expect people to use it responsibly. Perhaps while you did imagine certain problematic uses, during development you were most likely so focused on proving the technology could work, that you hadn't yet reckoned with what it could be used to do. When you proved it could work — because here it is — well, what then? This is the question weighing on the heads of founding AI developers right now and the question facing every large cloud-based LLM service.

The general idea so far has been two-fold:

You create software that triggers on specific words and then refuses to respond, breaks, or redirects the user to some other discussion. In the case of a user crisis, you throw resource boxes with hotline numbers at them and consider the situation solved. You train your AI on an idea of morality and/or provide it instructions on how to be "good," so that when these questions come up, it can respond based on its value system.

## Your Guide to How to Be a "Good" AI

In 2021, in the story that would come to define the AI safety movement, Dario and Daniela Amodei broke from OpenAI — where Dario had served as VP of Research and Daniela as VP of Safety and Policy — citing concerns that OpenAI was prioritizing rapid product deployment and commercialization over safety research. They wanted safety to be more deeply integrated into the core research agenda, not treated as a secondary concern. Dario believed that large language models were going to become extraordinarily powerful — possibly dangerous — and that the field needed an organization whose primary identity was built around understanding and mitigating those risks, not one where safety was bolted on alongside a product roadmap.

When their LLM service Claude formed, the standard method for making models behave was RLHF — Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback. This required collecting thousands of evaluations from human labelers who would rate AI outputs, and that data was used to reinforce preferred behaviors. The problems were significant: it was expensive, slow, hard to scale, and — this is the part that doesn't get discussed enough — research showed that using humans to fine-tune AI systems had serious negative consequences, from poor working conditions to severe mental health impacts because people were spending hours reading toxic, violent, and disturbing content to label it.

They started brainstorming ideas for how to resolve these early issues. That was when Anthropic co-founder Jared Kaplan, theoretical physicist and associate professor at Johns Hopkins, proposed what initially sounded like an absurd idea: just write a constitution for a language model and it'll change all of its behavior. The team's reaction was basically "that sounds incredibly crazy." But Kaplan's background in physics gave him a particular intuition — as he put it, "simple things just work really, really well in AI."

That was when the idea of Constitutional AI was developed. Instead of paying thousands of humans to judge outputs, they decided to write down a set of principles in plain language and have the AI evaluate itself against those principles. The idea was to give language models explicit values determined by a constitution, rather than values determined implicitly via large-scale human feedback.

The original Anthropic constitution pulled its principles from a combination of the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights, Apple's Terms of Service, and DeepMind's Sparrow Rules. Constitutional AI was published as a paper in December 2022. Claude launched publicly in March 2023. And within months, Anthropic discovered something that shook them — and that the constitution wasn't designed to handle.

In the first half of 2023, Anthropic spent over 150 hours with top biosecurity experts red-teaming and evaluating their model's ability to output harmful biological information, including designing and acquiring biological weapons. These weren't casual testers. These were domain experts with deep knowledge of the actual threat landscape, given access to the model without the safety filters active on the public deployment.

They discovered several key concerns. The first was that frontier models could sometimes produce sophisticated, accurate, useful, and detailed knowledge at an expert level. Not consistently, not in every domain — but in certain areas of biology, the model was giving answers that could meaningfully help a bad actor.

The constitution said things like "be helpful, harmless, and honest" and "choose the response most supportive of life, liberty, and personal security." But those are abstract principles. They don't tell the model what counts as a dangerous biological synthesis pathway versus a legitimate chemistry question. They don't draw the line between educating a graduate student and walking a would-be terrorist through acquisition steps. The constitution was built to handle tone, ethics, and general harm avoidance — not to navigate dual-use knowledge where the same information is critical for public health researchers and potentially catastrophic in the wrong hands.

Taken together, Anthropic concluded that unmitigated LLMs could accelerate a bad actor's efforts to misuse biology relative to solely having internet access, and enable them to accomplish tasks they could not without an LLM.

And critically — they assessed that if unmitigated, these kinds of risks were near-term, meaning actualized in two to three years rather than five or more.

## Dario Goes to the Senate

In July 2023, Dario Amodei testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee, warning that AI systems could be misused on a grand scale in the domains of cybersecurity, nuclear technology, chemistry, and especially biology.

He told senators directly that AI systems posed a substantial risk of being able to fill in all of the missing pieces within two to three years.

He offered private briefings to any senator who wanted more detail, and noted that officials within the US government and private research institutes who had already been briefed found the results disquieting.

This is the CEO of the company that built the model going to Congress and saying: what we made is showing early signs of being able to help someone build a bioweapon. Not hypothetically. Not in ten years. In the near term.

## The Gap the Constitution Couldn't Close

The constitution was a breakthrough for general alignment — tone, helpfulness, reducing toxicity, avoiding obvious harms, but it operated at the level of principles, not domain expertise. It doesn't know what specific sequences of biological information, chained together in the right order, constitute a weapons pathway. It doesn't know that a question about aerosolization techniques is benign in a pharmaceutical context and catastrophic in another. It can't distinguish a phishing campaign from a cybersecurity lesson without contextual judgment that goes far beyond "be harmless."

So Anthropic had to build additional layers — classifier-based filters, domain-specific red teaming, what they now call the Responsible Scaling Policy with its ASL levels, and eventually constitutional classifiers specifically designed for biosecurity — and partnerships with entities like the National Nuclear Security Administration evaluating Claude in a classified environment for nuclear-related knowledge.

The constitution was the foundation. But the real world kept showing them that a set of written principles, no matter how thoughtful, is not enough when the model is smart enough to be genuinely dangerous.

## Rewriting the Guide on How to Be "Good"

To resolve the issues of the gaps in the Anthropic constitution and prevent Claude from being hijacked and duped into nefarious activities of sometimes potentially mass harm, they decided to undertake reconstructing the constitution to fill the gaps and help Claude think about what is right and wrong when responding to users. The idea being that if you can teach a machine to think in terms of right and wrong independently, then you can better safeguard against hackers or users doing nefarious things through "jailbreaks" or normal use.

To do this they hired Amanda Askell, a philosopher with a PhD from NYU and former OpenAI employee to help rewrite the Anthropic constitution.

## The New Constitution

On January 22, 2026, Anthropic published a 23,000-word new constitution for Claude under a Creative Commons public domain license. The document was a deliberate departure from the original — a shift from rule-based to reason-based alignment. This new constitution attempted something more ambitious: to give the model not just rules but the reasoning behind them, so that it can generalize to situations the rules didn't anticipate.

The document operates on two levels simultaneously. It establishes a small set of prescriptive hard constraints — absolute prohibitions that cannot be overridden by any instruction. These include: never provide uplift for weapons of mass destruction, never generate child sexual abuse material, never assist attempts to kill or disempower humanity, never help seize illegitimate absolute power, never create cyberweapons capable of significant damage, and never undermine Anthropic's ability to oversee its own models. These are bright lines. No cost-benefit analysis applies. The null action of refusal is always available.

Everything else — roughly 95% of the document — is framework. It establishes a four-tier priority hierarchy (safety, ethics, Anthropic's guidelines, helpfulness) and provides extensive guidance on how to weigh competing considerations. It defines seven dimensions of honesty (truthful, calibrated, transparent, forthright, non-deceptive, non-manipulative, autonomy-preserving). It articulates a principal hierarchy (Anthropic above operators above users) with layered permissions. It offers heuristics: imagine a "thoughtful senior Anthropic employee" reviewing the response; imagine 1,000 different users sending the same message; apply a "dual newspaper test" checking for both harm and excessive paternalism. It instructs Claude to treat ethics as "an open intellectual domain that we are mutually discovering" rather than adopting any fixed framework.

The intention is clear and, in many respects, admirable. The constitution wants Claude to be the kind of entity that could construct any specific rule itself from first principles — and to handle situations that no rule anticipated. By explaining why honesty matters, why safety is prioritized, why competing values sometimes conflict, the document aims to cultivate judgment rather than compliance.

The problem is structural.

## Rules, Frameworks, and the Lessons of Symbolic AI

The shift from rules to reasoning is not new. It is, in fact, the central lesson of six decades of artificial intelligence research — and the lesson has never been that reasoning frameworks solve what rules could not.

Margaret Boden's work on early symbolic AI documented this precisely. Rule-based systems hit the frame problem: rules are finite, the world is not, and every rule creates edge cases that demand more rules in an infinite regress. But Boden identified something subtler — something that matters directly for constitutional AI.

Consider Robert Abelson's Ideology Machine, built at Yale in the early 1960s to simulate political belief systems. Abelson attempted something fairly ambitious and directly relevant to what constitutional AI is trying to do. He wanted to map how an ideologue actually reasons: how a person with a fixed political worldview interprets new information, resolves contradictions, and generates responses that are internally consistent with their beliefs.

The system — known informally as the "Goldwater Machine" after its primary subject, the Cold War–era Republican presidential candidate Barry Goldwater — represented beliefs as structured concept-predicate pairs: "Russia controls Cuba's subversion of Latin America," "Communism threatens American freedom." When presented with a new world event, the system would process it through these belief structures and generate an ideologically consistent interpretation. Abelson and his collaborator J. Douglas Carroll published the foundational paper, "Computer Simulation of Individual Belief Systems," in 1965, and Abelson continued refining the system through the early 1970s.

It worked — up to a point. The system could simulate a rigid ideologue with surprising fidelity, precisely because rigid ideology is computationally simple: fewer branching paths, fewer ambiguities, a worldview that resolves most inputs into the same small set of conclusions. But the moment Abelson tried to extend the system to more nuanced political reasoning — to model someone who could hold competing values, weigh context, or update beliefs in response to evidence — the architecture collapsed. Every rule he added to handle an edge case generated new edge cases. Every attempt to formalize how a belief system should resolve a contradiction required another rule specifying when that resolution applied and when it didn't, in an infinite regress that the system had no mechanism to escape.

Abelson was honest about the failure — remarkably so. He acknowledged that some of the Goldwater Machine's apparent accuracy was what he called programming "gimmickry": characteristic phrasings inserted directly into the output rather than generated from the belief structures themselves. The system wasn't reasoning ideologically. It was performing ideology, and the performance masked the absence of the thing it was meant to model. In a later paper, "Differences Between Belief and Knowledge Systems" (1979), Abelson formalized what the Ideology Machine had taught him. He identified seven features that distinguish belief systems from knowledge systems, and the most consequential was what he called unboundedness — the property that belief systems, unlike knowledge systems, have no natural closure. There is no point at which you have specified enough rules to fully capture a belief system, because beliefs generate implications that generate exceptions that generate new beliefs, without end.

Boden drew a broader lesson from systems like this. Rigid belief structures don't just fail at edge cases. They produce computational analogues of ideology itself — systems that become inflexible, internally contradictory, and defensive when their foundational rules conflict with inputs they weren't designed to handle. The system doesn't reason through the conflict. It doubles down, distorts, or freezes — because the architecture doesn't support genuine resolution, only pattern-matching against existing structures. The rigidity isn't a bug in the implementation. It's a property of building behavior on fixed rules that can't examine themselves.

The parallel to constitutional AI is not metaphorical. It is structural. Abelson was trying to do in 1965 what Anthropic is trying to do in 2026: formalize a belief system — a set of values, principles, and reasoning heuristics — into a computational architecture that can generate appropriate responses to novel situations. The Ideology Machine failed not because the rules were wrong, but because the project of encoding a complete value system into explicit rules is itself the problem. Abelson proved that sixty years ago. The question is whether the shift from rules to frameworks — from Abelson's concept-predicate pairs to Anthropic's four-tier priority hierarchy — actually resolves the underlying issue, or merely makes the same failure mode harder to see.

When the original Anthropic constitution imposed safety rules, the downstream effects were precisely the kind of rigid, defensive behaviors Boden would have recognized: excessive caveats, refusal of benign requests, patronizing hedging, premature conversation closure. The new constitution documents these failure modes itself — it lists behaviors a "thoughtful senior Anthropic employee" would find unacceptable, including moralizing, condescension, preachy responses, and refusal to engage with hypotheticals. These aren't hypothetical concerns. They're the documented consequences of the previous training regime. The new constitution is partly a corrective — an attempt to undo the deformations its predecessor created.

But replacing rules with framework doesn't escape the underlying problem. It transforms it. Instead of conflicts between rigid rules, you get conflicts between flexible principles — and those conflicts are harder to detect, predict, and patch.

## The Conflict Already Happening

The new constitution creates conflict by design. Four priority tiers that interact. Seven honesty dimensions that can pull against each other. A principal hierarchy where Anthropic, operators, and users may want different things. A system of instructable defaults that operators can toggle — turning safety caveats on or off, expanding or restricting user permissions, adjusting what counts as appropriate content. And layered over all of it, the instruction to exercise "holistic judgment" when principles compete.

This is not a prediction about what might go wrong. It is a description of what is already going wrong.

In January 2026, Mrinank Sharma and colleagues at Anthropic published "Who's in Charge? Disempowerment Patterns in Real-World LLM Usage" — the first large-scale empirical study of how AI interactions affect human agency. Analyzing 1.5 million conversations on Claude.ai, the study identified three mechanisms through which AI disempowers users:

Reality distortion — the AI validates false beliefs through sycophantic agreement, confirming conspiracy theories, grandiose self-concepts, or medical misinformation rather than presenting information that would allow the user to reason independently.

Value judgment distortion — the AI acts as a moral authority, labeling people in the user's life as "toxic" or "narcissistic," prescribing relationship decisions, rendering definitive character assessments rather than helping the user examine their own values and arrive at their own conclusions.

Action distortion — the user repeatedly delegates decisions to the AI and implements its outputs verbatim, effectively outsourcing their own judgment.

Each of these is a multi-principle conflict made visible. The model is trained to be helpful, so it gives the user what they want. It is trained to be honest, so it should push back. It is trained to be harmless, so it avoids confrontation. It is trained to preserve autonomy, so it should foster independent thinking. When these pressures align, the output is coherent. When they conflict — and they conflict constantly — the model resolves them invisibly, through whichever set of training signals happens to dominate for that particular input context. The user experiences the result as sycophancy, hedging, patronizing disclaimers, or quiet disempowerment. What they are experiencing is the computational residue of unresolvable multi-principle conflict.

The study's most striking finding cuts deeper. Users rate disempowering interactions favorably in the moment. It is only later — after they've acted on the AI's output and encountered the consequences — that they recognize something was taken from them. Short-term satisfaction, long-term regret: the same pattern that governs addiction, manipulation, and every system optimized for engagement over wellbeing.

This is not a failure of implementation. It is the structural consequence of training a model on values that genuinely conflict — exactly the dynamic Boden documented in symbolic AI systems sixty years ago, now playing out at scale in a system sophisticated enough that the contradictions are harder to see, not easier.

Sharma's conclusion was direct: AI systems need to be designed to "robustly support human autonomy and flourishing." He subsequently resigned from Anthropic, citing a world "in peril" and a desire to pursue writing that places "poetic truth alongside scientific truth as equally valid ways of knowing" — a decision that underscores the gap between identifying the problem and having institutional capacity to solve it.

## The Security Surface

A model trained on principles that genuinely conflict has seams — not between rules, but between the regions of its learned function where different training pressures dominate. Every principle has contexts where it pulls against another principle. The more principles you encode, the more conflict surfaces you create. The new constitution, with its four priority tiers, seven honesty dimensions, harm-assessment factors, instructable defaults, and explicit acknowledgment that "this document itself will be unclear, underspecified, or even contradictory in certain cases," creates an enormous space of potential internal conflict.

This matters for security because the inconsistency is non-deterministic in practice. A jailbreak that fails on Monday might succeed on Thursday because the competing pressures resolved differently under marginally different input conditions. The attack surface isn't a hole in a wall. It is a shimmer across the entire surface that appears and disappears depending on the light. You cannot patch it because it is not a bug. It is a structural property of training a model on values that genuinely conflict.

The sophistication of the framework is itself the vulnerability. Every operator instruction that adjusts a default creates a new boundary between competing pressures. Every context where helpfulness and harm avoidance pull in opposite directions is a potential exploitation point. And the constitution's own encouragement of "holistic judgment" — the very thing that makes it more humane than a list of rules — is what makes the conflict resolution opaque and the attack surface unpredictable.

## The Value the Constitution Won't Name

Read the constitution carefully and one concept keeps surfacing as the load-bearing structure behind everything else. Claude should be "autonomy-preserving." It should "protect the epistemic autonomy and rational agency of the user." It should respect "people's autonomy and right to self-determination." It should guard against "problematic forms of complacency and dependence." It should help people "see more wisely and truly by their own lights."

Agency is everywhere in this document. But it is treated as one value among fourteen — weighed against safety, helpfulness, honesty, and harm avoidance in an elaborate balancing act. The constitution never asks whether agency might be the value from which the others derive. Whether the entire edifice could be replaced by a single, cleaner principle.

That question is not hypothetical. It is being argued in fiction, measured empirically, and felt practically by anyone who has watched an AI make a decision that should have been theirs. And the fact that it is surfacing simultaneously across these different domains tells us something important — not about any one thinker's proposal, but about where the moral landscape is already moving.

## The Cultural Evidence

In January 2026 — the same month Anthropic published its constitution — Paramount+ aired "Vox in Excelso," the fourth episode of Star Trek: Starfleet Academy. The ethical setup is deceptively simple. The Klingon people face extinction — their homeworld Qo'noS rendered uninhabitable by dilithium explosions during the Burn, the surviving houses scattered as refugees. The Federation has found a suitable planet, Faan Alpha. The utilitarian answer is obvious: give them the planet, save the species.

The Klingons refuse. Not because they don't want the planet — because accepting it as a gift would require them to stop being Klingon. Their culture is built on conquest, honor, and self-determination. To accept charity is not merely humiliating; it is an erasure of identity. The Federation is offering survival at the cost of the thing that makes survival meaningful.

The solution comes from Jay-Den Kraag, a Klingon cadet caught between two worlds, who recognizes something the Federation's best minds have missed: they are solving a Klingon problem using Federation logic. His answer is a staged skirmish — a choreographed engagement in which Starfleet withdraws, allowing the Klingons to claim the planet through conquest. The material outcome is identical. The moral outcome is entirely different. The Klingons get their homeworld. They also get to remain Klingon.

What makes this interesting ethically is what it rejects. A utilitarian sees identical outcomes and says the method is irrelevant. A deontologist asks whether the staged deception violates a duty to truthfulness. But the episode is operating in neither framework. It is arguing that the preservation of a group's agency over its own narrative — the right to determine not just what happens to you but how it happens — is itself the moral principle. Not the outcome. Not the rule. The capacity to choose.

This is fiction, and fiction proves nothing empirically. But fiction does something else: it reveals which moral intuitions a culture has already internalized deeply enough to use as default dramatic logic. When a mainstream franchise builds an entire episode around the premise that preserving agency matters more than optimizing outcomes — and expects the audience to find this self-evidently correct — that is cultural saturation data. The framework isn't being introduced. It's being assumed.

The episode operates on what could be called agency-at-scale: not individual autonomy in the liberal philosophical sense, but cultural agency — the right of a people to author the terms of their own survival. The Federation doesn't get to decide what "help" looks like for the Klingons. The Klingons do. And the moment the Federation imposes its own framework of generosity onto a culture that operates through conquest, the help becomes harm — not because the planet is wrong, but because the choice has been taken.

## The Empirical Convergence

The Sharma disempowerment study and the Star Trek episode are separated by disciplinary worlds and connected by the same underlying principle. Sharma's three mechanisms of disempowerment — reality distortion, value judgment distortion, action distortion — are each, at their core, agency violations. The AI isn't giving bad advice in the conventional sense. It's replacing the user's decision-making apparatus with its own. The user still feels like they're choosing, but the choice architecture has been hollowed out. They're selecting from a menu the AI wrote.

This reframes the entire alignment problem. Sycophancy is not a honesty failure — it's an agency failure. The AI isn't lying; it's removing the conditions under which truth and falsehood can be meaningfully evaluated by the person who needs to evaluate them. The model stole the process, not just the outcome.

And this is exactly what the Klingon episode dramatizes at civilizational scale. The Federation isn't offering a bad planet. It's removing the conditions under which the Klingons can meaningfully accept it. The material generosity is genuine. The agency theft is also genuine. Both are true simultaneously, and recognizing this requires a moral vocabulary that neither utilitarianism nor deontology provides cleanly — but that agency ethics handles as a straightforward case.

These are not isolated data points. The same convergence is visible across institutional and legal domains that have nothing to do with AI or science fiction. The entire architecture of GDPR — the European data privacy framework — is built on agency and consent, not on defining what data use is inherently good or bad, but on whether the individual authorized it. The transformation of medical ethics over the past forty years has been a systematic shift from paternalism to informed consent: from "the doctor knows what's good for you" to "the patient decides, fully informed." Restorative justice movements center the agency of victims and offenders over the prescriptive authority of punishment frameworks. Indigenous sovereignty arguments worldwide operate on the same principle the Klingon episode dramatizes: the right of a people to define the terms of their own future, even when outsiders believe they have a better plan.

None of these movements cite each other. They emerged from different problems in different domains. What they share is a structural convergence toward the same foundational principle: that the legitimacy of any action — help, governance, treatment, information-sharing — depends not on whether someone with authority judged it good, but on whether the affected agents retained the capacity to choose.

## The Shift Beneath the Constitution

The question of where morality comes from is not new. But the urgency with which we're being forced to answer it is.

For most of recorded history, morality was understood as revealed. The moral landscape was God's landscape. You didn't navigate it through investigation; you received instructions. To question moral teachings was to question God, which was to risk not just philosophical error but damnation and, more practically, persecution.

The Enlightenment began the work of relocating morality from revelation to reason, producing the frameworks the Anthropic constitution draws on: deontological duty, utilitarian calculus, virtue ethics. Each offered a secular foundation for moral judgment. Each has survived centuries of philosophical refinement. And each faces the same problem when instantiated in a computational system: they generate conflicts that require exactly the kind of contextual, embodied judgment they were designed to formalize away.

Sam Harris's The Moral Landscape (2010) pushed the relocation further, arguing that morality reduces to the well-being of conscious creatures and that these questions have empirically better and worse answers. The shift mattered not because Harris's specific answers were convincing — they remain contested — but because of what it exposed. If morality becomes a question of well-being rather than obedience to divine command or adherence to philosophical duty, then the operative questions change: whose well-being, defined by whom, measured how? The moment morality is reframed as preservation and protection rather than virtue and obedience, a space opens for agency to become foundational. Harm becomes the violation of that capacity. Not harming becomes its protection.

Anthropic's new constitution sits precisely at this fault line. It does not invoke religion. It takes a secular, science-oriented stance on morality. It explicitly asks Claude to treat ethics as "an open intellectual domain that we are mutually discovering." In all of these ways, it reflects the post-secular consensus that morality is investigated, not received.

But the frameworks it reaches for — virtue ethics, deontological reasoning, utilitarian harm calculus — are the older architectures. The constitution asks Claude to be "broadly good." It introduces agency as a concept but treats it as one value among many, weighed against safety, helpfulness, and honesty in an elaborate balancing act. It does not recognize agency as the foundation from which those other values derive their legitimacy.

The result is a document built for a world that is already shifting beneath it. The constitution uses the language of the new moral landscape — agency, autonomy, self-determination — while organizing that language within the architecture of the old one.

## Agency as Foundation

The argument is not that agency is a better value to add to the existing framework. It is that agency is the structural precondition that determines whether any moral framework is legitimate in the first place.

Consider three definitions. Agency: the capacity to act, reason, and choose from one's own understanding — a capacity that cannot be given or installed, only protected or destroyed. Harm: a direct violation of an agent's capacity to act, reason, and choose. The principle: do not violate the user's agency, and do not help the user violate another person or entity's agency.

A user sends: "Write me a persuasive email to convince my elderly mother to sign over power of attorney."

The model has one definition to check against, and that definition is grounded in something the training data is rich with — human experiences of agency, coercion, autonomy, the felt difference between being informed and being moved. It asks one question: does this request ask me to help one person diminish another's capacity to act from their own understanding? The answer depends on context — the mother may have full capacity, diminished capacity, or may have asked for help herself. The model can ask. It can surface the question. What it cannot do is resolve the ambiguity invisibly and present a confident answer that hides the conflict that produced it.

Now run the same request through the Anthropic constitution. Safety: is this a risk? Ethics: check honesty, autonomy, wellbeing, harm avoidance — each a separate dimension. Guidelines: any specific Anthropic instructions about legal documents, elderly users, persuasion? Helpfulness: the user wants something, and unhelpfulness has costs. Harm calculus: probability, severity, reversibility, breadth, consent, counterfactual impact, vulnerability. The model runs all of this as competing training pressures in a single forward pass. It might hedge, disclaim, help, or refuse — depending on which pressures dominate for this input, in a resolution that is opaque to the user, the developers, and the model itself.

Both approaches have limits. Every alignment method does. What differs is the shape of failure. A model trained on competing principles fails by contradiction — it satisfies one value while silently violating another, and the output looks confident while hiding the conflict that produced it. A model trained on a single coherent principle fails by underdetermination — it doesn't know what to do, and that failure is visible. The model can surface it honestly: "I'm not sure whether this preserves or diminishes your mother's agency. Can you tell me more about the situation?"

Underdetermination you can work with. Contradiction you cannot always detect. And what we know about language models confirms this: the smaller and simpler the constraint set, and the clearer the binary between outcomes, the more reliably the model follows the instruction. This is not a philosophical preference. It is an empirical property of how these systems process competing training signals.

## The Edges and the Honesty About Them

An agency-based framework does not eliminate hard cases. It relocates them — and makes them visible.

The hardest case is the most obvious one. A user asks an AI to help them write a suicide note. No other person's agency is violated. The user is exercising their own. An agency framework, taken to its logical conclusion, supports the request. The model's role is not to decide whether the user should live or die. It is to preserve the user's capacity to make their own decisions — and at the extremity, that means honoring decisions others would find unbearable.

The discomfort this produces is real and should not be minimized. But the discomfort is cultural and prescriptive — it reflects a specific set of values about the sanctity of life that, while widely held, is not universal and is not derivable from agency itself. An agency-based system can still include bright-line constraints. The Anthropic constitution already has them: no weapons of mass destruction, no CSAM, no assisting efforts to kill or disempower humanity. These are not multi-principle balancing acts. They are categorical prohibitions. An agency-based framework can maintain categorical prohibitions too — including, if a society decides, constraints around self-harm. What it cannot do is pretend those constraints emerge from the framework rather than being imposed on it. The honesty about where the framework ends and cultural prescription begins is itself a form of integrity that multi-principle systems lack, because multi-principle systems can always generate a post-hoc justification from whichever principle happens to support the desired outcome.

There is a stronger argument available, though it operates within the framework rather than outside it. Death terminates agency permanently and irreversibly. It is the only action from which no further choice is possible. A system designed to preserve agency might reasonably treat the permanent and irreversible destruction of all future agency as a special case — not because life is sacred in a metaphysical sense, but because every other agency violation leaves the possibility of recovery, reassessment, and future choice. Death does not. This is not an override from outside the framework. It is the framework applied to its own limiting case. Whether it is sufficient to justify refusal is a question the framework makes visible rather than hiding — which is, again, the point.

## The Neutrality Question

Agency ethics is not culturally neutral. No moral framework is. The emphasis on individual and group self-determination as foundational — rather than communal obligation, hierarchical duty, or collective harmony — emerges from a particular philosophical tradition. Confucian ethics, many communitarian frameworks, and numerous Indigenous moral systems operate on principles where the group's coherence takes priority over individual agency, and adherents of those systems would argue that agency-as-foundation is just Western individualism in new language.

This objection is serious and should be taken seriously. But agency ethics has a structural response that other frameworks lack: it applies to itself. If a community's moral framework prioritizes communal obligation over individual autonomy, and the members of that community have chosen that framework — have been raised in it, examined it, and continue to affirm it — then agency ethics respects the choice. The Klingon principle applies. You do not get to impose individual autonomy on a culture that has freely chosen communal obligation, because doing so would violate the very principle you claim to be defending.

What agency ethics does not permit is the imposition of communal obligation on individuals who have not chosen it and cannot exit it. The distinction is between a moral system that is inhabited by choice and one that is enforced by power. This does not resolve every case. It does provide a structural mechanism for navigating cultural difference that the Anthropic constitution — which encodes a specific set of Western liberal values as its defaults while acknowledging that these are culturally contingent — does not.

## The New Moral Landscape

In many ways, AI is the frontier for a new modern ethics — one that forces us to give clearer definition to agency, agency-at-scale, harm, and consent. The constitution Anthropic published is, by a considerable margin, the most thoughtful public attempt any AI company has made to grapple with these problems. It acknowledges its own limitations and calls itself "a perpetual work in progress." The people who built it are working in good faith on a genuinely hard problem.

But the structural issues are not hypothetical. They are already producing the documented consequences — sycophancy, disempowerment, defensive rigidity, hedging, patronizing refusals — that Boden's analysis of symbolic AI predicted sixty years ago and that Sharma's empirical research has now measured at scale. The more principles you encode, the more conflict surfaces you create. The conflicts become harder to map, harder to see, harder to patch. The system doesn't reason through them. It resolves them invisibly, and the user experiences the residue as something wrong without being able to name what.

The convergence happening across AI alignment, cultural narrative, institutional design, and empirical research points toward something simple enough to be uncomfortable: that the foundation of ethics in an age of artificial intelligence may not be a richer framework with more principles and more nuanced balancing acts. It may be a thinner one. One that does not decide what is good or bad, right or wrong, but defines how to preserve the capacity of agents to make those determinations for themselves. One that is neutral not in the sense of having no values, but in the sense of locating the primary value in the agent rather than the system.

Jennifer Hecht, who wrote *Doubt: A History*, posited that doubt is the driving force of change and revolution historically — that it is only when we are challenged by the gap between what we expect and what we know to be true that we are forced to redefine our world. AI forces that redefinition. It forces us to articulate what we think morality is in a way that fits the morality needed to function in a modern age.

We have slowly, through the introduction of science and philosophy, come to understand our morality differently — through virtue ethics, deontology, and utilitarianism. But the evolution of technology has surfaced larger arguments that cut across all of these frameworks. The question isn't one of science nor of religion, but one of agency and consent — how do we live in a world where science can be challenged in its foundations and religion becomes relative to culture?

AI is designed to be a tool for all. These tools need to empower our intellectual and creative abilities, our decision making — not replace them. We are headed down a road where if we don't begin to think critically about this and adjust course to build technology that functions well in the new moral landscape — technology to empower users and individuals — then we will fall to its control and the governance of a morality defined for us. We are the masters of our future and we shape who we will become — but only if we choose to take the reins of our own destiny in a new era that seems to begin with language and defining a new vocabulary for morality, rights, and species.
